node.text: 🎥 @paulnicklen : The ocean has been a mystery for much of human history (and still is to a large extent), but life here is often more familiar than not. Our conservation mission is built on the principle that it becomes easier to speak up on behalf of vulnerable wildlife when we see a little of ourselves in them, and few stories have the power to connect us like those of a mother's love. #Whale #Beluga #Humpback #HumpbackWhale #Mother #Offspring #Babies #Conservation #Storytelling #MothersLove

node.text:
Me arriving at my fridge after working 14 hours without eating 😆
Fin Whale 🐋.
The fin whale is the second largest animal to ever live, in the entire history of Earth. Reaching lengths of at least 85 feet (26 m) and weights of 80 tons, this species is second only to its close relative, the blue whale. Their incredible size is only possible because of their aquatic lifestyles and the buoyancy provided by seawater. On land, an animal as large as the fin whale would almost certainly be crushed under its own weight.
🎥 @dolphindronedom
#sea #whale #ocean #nature

When fishes stop swimming and start walking!😲

These amazing videos were filmed by @benmantagilit at @mantadivegilit

node.text:
Taricaya turtle release! 🐢💚
These turtles have suffered greatly due to lack of human conscience, the effects of gold mining and the contamination of their habitat. Now these little ones have a new opportunity thanks to the Taricaya Turtle Repopulation Project! @taricaya.eco.reserve

Video by @mikaelaswildlife & @taricaya.eco.reserve

Mikaela said: “Every night we go out searching for their eggs on the beach before they can be taken for food, incubate them at camp and then release them back into the wild where they belong!” 🙏🏽
#sea
